For proceedings of the conference in honor of Martin Reuter: "Quantum
  Fields---From Fundamental Concepts to Phenomenological Questions"; 14 pages;
  based in part on my review article arXiv:1705.05417

column11:
  In this work we solve in closed form the system of difference equations
\begin{equation*}
  x_{n+1}=\dfrac{ay_nx_{n-1}+bx_{n-1}+c}{y_nx_{n-1}},\;
y_{n+1}=\dfrac{ax_ny_{n-1}+by_{n-1}+c}{x_ny_{n-1}},\;n=0,1,..., \end{equation*}
where the initial values $x_{-1}$, $x_0$, $y_{-1}$ and $y_0$ are arbitrary
nonzero real numbers and the parameters $a$, $b$ and $c$ are arbitrary real
numbers with $c\ne 0$. In particular we represent the solutions of some
particular cases of this system in terms of Tribonacci and Padovan numbers and
we prove the global stability of the corresponding positive equilibrium points.
The result obtained here extend those obtained in some recent papers.
